Forward Models

Single DMA

Constant Voltage

The DMA is operated in classifier mode and set to a single voltage. The mobility classified particles are then passed to one or more detectors. Transmission can be modeled by the convolution of the particle Charging Probability, DMA Transfer Function, and Transmission Loss through the DMA. These are built into the DMA Grid. Therefore a net transmission function can be written:

Info

The net transmission function T describes transmission through the DMA, including the charge filter, the DMA transfer function, and the DMA transmission efficiency. 

T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥) = Œ¥.Œ©(Œõ,Œ¥.Z,zÀ¢/k).*Œ¥.Tc(k,Œ¥.Dp).*Œ¥.Tl(Œõ,Œ¥.Dp)

where Œõ is the DMA configuration, Œ¥ the DMA grid, zÀ¢ is the z-star selected by the DMA, and k is the number of charges.

The following example shows ho to use T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥) to predict the mobility distribution exiting the DMA. In the code fragment

  • zÀ¢ is the z-star selected by the DMA
  • ùïü·∂ú‚Åø is an assumed known bimodal lognormal distribution computed on the DMA size grid
  • ‚Ñï is an array of transmitted mobility distributions carrying k charges
  • ùïÑ is an array of transmitted apparent mobility distributions carrying k charges
  • ùïü‚Çú, ùïû‚Çú are the superposition of these distributions
using DifferentialMobilityAnalyzers

# Create a DMA config
qsa,qsh = 1.66e-5, 8.33e-5                       # Qsample [m3 s-1], Qsheath [m3 s-1]
t,p = 295.15, 1e5                                # Temperature [K], Pressure [Pa]
r‚ÇÅ,r‚ÇÇ,l = 9.37e-3,1.961e-2,0.44369               # DMA geometry [m]
Œõ = DMAconfig(t,p,qsa,qsh,r‚ÇÅ,r‚ÇÇ,l,0.0,:-,6,:cylindrical)

# Create a DMA grid
z‚ÇÅ,z‚ÇÇ = vtoz(Œõ,10000), vtoz(Œõ,10)    # bins, upper, lower mobility limit
Œ¥ = setupDMA(Œõ, z‚ÇÅ, z‚ÇÇ, 512);

# Compute the transmission through the DMA
T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥) = Œ¥.Œ©(Œõ,Œ¥.Z,zÀ¢/k).*Œ¥.Tc(k,Œ¥.Dp).*Œ¥.Tl(Œõ,Œ¥.Dp)
zÀ¢ = dtoz(Œõ, 100*1e-9)
ùïü·∂ú‚Åø = DMALognormalDistribution([[900., 40., 1.5], [500., 180., 1.4]], Œ¥)
‚Ñï = map(k -> T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥)*ùïü·∂ú‚Åø,1:3)
ùïÑ = map(k -> (ztod(Œõ,1,zÀ¢)/ztod(Œõ,k,zÀ¢))‚ãÖ(T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥)*ùïü·∂ú‚Åø),1:3)
ùïü‚Çú, ùïû‚Çú = sum(‚Ñï), sum(ùïÑ)

Figure. Left: assumed bimodal lognormal size distribution. Middle: monodisperse mobility size distribution plotted against the apparent +1 mobility diameter, defined as the apparent setpoint diameter of the DMA. Dashed line is total number concentration. Right: same as middle panel but plotted versus the mobility diameter.

The DMA selects approximately a triangular distribution around mobility centroid $z^s$. The distribution is symmetric when plotted against the log of mobility, but asymmetric when plotted against the log of the apparent +1 mobility diameter because the Cunningham slip flow correction factor applied in the conversion from mobility to diameter is a strong function of particle size. The majority of selected particles are singly charged, but the contribution of multiply charged particles to the total number is not negligible. The mobility distribution has contributions from particles that are at least twice the diameter of the selected centroid diameter. The relative fractions are determined by the equilibrium charge fraction and the number of particles available at each diameter.

Info

The map(k->f, 1:3) construct sequentially applies values from the array [1,2,3] to k and calls the function f. The output is an array of length 3. Since T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥) produces a vector, ùïü·∂ú‚Åø is a size distribution, and vector * size distribution is a size distribution, the output of

‚Ñï = map(k -> T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥)*ùïü·∂ú‚Åø,1:3)

is an array of size distributions.

For more information see Figure 2 in the Manuscript, check out Session 2 of the Tutorial and/or Notebook S4 in the Notebooks section.

Complete Distribution

If the DMA is stepped or scanned, the response function can be computed from the convolution Matrix ùêÄ and the known true size distribution. The operation matrix * size distribution is defined in the Operators section. Thus we can conveniently write ùï£ = ùêÄ * ùïü to compute the response function.

Œ¥ = setupDMA(Œõ, z‚ÇÅ, z‚ÇÇ, 60);
ùïü = DMALognormalDistribution([[400, 30, 1.2],[500, 110, 1.7]], Œ¥)
ùï£ = Œ¥.ùêÄ * ùïü

Tandem DMAs

Humidified Tandem DMA

Single Composition

Dried, charge equilibrated particles are classified in DMA1. The flow is split to measure particle concentration with a condensation particle counter (CPC). The remaining flow is passed through a humidifier. Hygroscopic particles take up water and increase in diameter. The humidified size distribution is measured using the second DMA that is operated in scanning or stepping mode. Passage through a second bipolar charger (charge neutralizer) is optional and rarely used in TDMA experiments.

To model transmission through the tandem DMA we need to

  • setup two DMAs, Œ¥‚ÇÅ and Œ¥‚ÇÇ
  • know the input size distribution
  • formulate a transmission model

Setting up DMAs is described in DMA Configuration. The input size distribution is assumed based on a lognormal distribution. The constructor function DMALognormalDistribution initializes a lognormal distribution along a DMA grid.

Ax = [[1300.0, 60.0, 1.4], [2000.0, 200.0, 1.6]]
ùïü·∂ú‚Åø = DMALognormalDistribution(Ax, Œ¥‚ÇÅ)

The transmission model is a combination of operating DMA‚ÇÅ at Constant Voltage and transmission of a Complete Distribution through DMA‚ÇÇ. 

# Tandem DMA equations
T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) = Œ¥.Œ©(Œõ, Œ¥.Z, zÀ¢ / k) .* Œ¥.Tc(k, Œ¥.Dp) .* Œ¥.Tl(Œõ, Œ¥.Dp) 
DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ, Œ¥) =
    sum(map(k -> (ztod(Œõ, 1, zÀ¢) / ztod(Œõ, k, zÀ¢)) ‚ãÖ (gf ‚ãÖ (T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) * ùïü)), 1:3))
DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥) = Œ¥.ùêé * ùïü
model(zÀ¢, gf) = DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü·∂ú‚Åø, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ‚ÇÅ, Œ¥‚ÇÅ) |> ùïü -> DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥‚ÇÇ)

The function T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) is already known. The function DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ, Œ¥) takes a distribution ùïü and mobility zÀ¢ and passes it through DMA Œõ, Œ¥. The inner function computes the mobility distributions ùïÑ = map(k -> (ztod(Œõ,1,zÀ¢)/ztod(Œõ,k,zÀ¢))‚ãÖ(T(zÀ¢,k,Œõ,Œ¥)*ùïü·∂ú‚Åø),1:3) as in the Constant Voltage example. However, the output of DMA‚ÇÅ is shifted by gf through gf ‚ãÖ (T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) * ùïü).

Note

The dot product of scalar ‚ãÖ SizeDistribution shifts the size distribution in diameter space: Size Operators. Check out the Tutorial Session 1 and/or Notebook S3 in the Notebooks section for visualizations.

The resulting ùïÑ distributions are summed over all charges. The output of DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ, Œ¥) is the mobility distribution passed through DMA‚ÇÅ and shifted uniformly by the growth factor gf.

The function DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥) takes an input size distribution ùïü and passes it through DMA‚ÇÇ. No neutralizer is used. Therefore the convolution Matrix ùêé is applied.

Finally, the function model(zÀ¢, gf) chains DMA‚ÇÅ and DMA‚ÇÇ together. The output of DMA‚ÇÅ is piped as input to the function DMA‚ÇÇ. Below is the complete example, which produces the response function of the tandem DMA.

# Setup two DMAs Œ¥‚ÇÅ and Œ¥‚ÇÇ
t, p = 295.15, 1e5
qsa, Œ≤ = 1.66e-5, 1 / 5
r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l = 9.37e-3, 1.961e-2, 0.44369
Œõ‚ÇÅ = DMAconfig(t, p, qsa, qsa / Œ≤, r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l, 0.0, :-, 3, :cylindrical)
Œõ‚ÇÇ = DMAconfig(t, p, qsa, qsa / Œ≤, r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l, 0.0, :-, 3, :cylindrical)
bins, z‚ÇÅ, z‚ÇÇ = 512, dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 500e-9), dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 30e-9)
Œ¥‚ÇÅ = setupDMA(Œõ‚ÇÅ, z‚ÇÅ, z‚ÇÇ, bins)
Œ¥‚ÇÇ = setupDMA(Œõ‚ÇÇ, z‚ÇÅ, z‚ÇÇ, bins)

# Pick a known upstream size distribution
Ax = [[1300.0, 60.0, 1.4], [2000.0, 200.0, 1.6]]
ùïü·∂ú‚Åø = DMALognormalDistribution(Ax, Œ¥‚ÇÅ)

# Tandem DMA equations
T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) = Œ¥.Œ©(Œõ, Œ¥.Z, zÀ¢ / k) .* Œ¥.Tc(k, Œ¥.Dp) .* Œ¥.Tl(Œõ, Œ¥.Dp)
DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ, Œ¥) =
    sum(map(k -> (ztod(Œõ, 1, zÀ¢) / ztod(Œõ, k, zÀ¢)) ‚ãÖ (gf ‚ãÖ (T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) * ùïü)), 1:3))
DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥) = Œ¥.ùêé * ùïü
model(zÀ¢, gf) = DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü·∂ú‚Åø, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ‚ÇÅ, Œ¥‚ÇÅ) |> ùïü -> DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥‚ÇÇ)

# Pass size distribution to DMA‚ÇÅ and then output distributiom to DMA‚ÇÇ
zÀ¢ = dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 100e-9);   # Mobility of 100 nm particle
gf = 1.55                # Growth factor
ùïû = model(zÀ¢, gf)

Multiple Compositions

The DMA output of a heterogenous population can be written from the tandem DMA model

model(zÀ¢, gf) = DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü·∂ú‚Åø, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ‚ÇÅ, Œ¥‚ÇÅ) |> ùïü -> DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥‚ÇÇ)
P = [0.5,0.15, 0.10, 0.25]   # Probability of growth factor (4 populations)
gf = [1.0, 1.2, 1.6, 2.1]    # Values of growth factor
zÀ¢ = dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 100e-9)        # Mobility of 100 nm particle
ùïû = sum(map(i->(P[i]*model(zÀ¢, gf[i])), 1:length(P)))  # The growth factor distribution

This assumes 4 population each having a unique growth factor and fractional contribution to the total distribution. If the fractions are known, the net response function of the TDMA is readily computed. The map function results in 4 model distribution, one for each population. The sum function superimposes them into a single distribution. 

Ax = [[1300.0, 60.0, 1.4], [2000.0, 200.0, 1.6]]
ùïü·∂ú‚Åø = DMALognormalDistribution(Ax, Œ¥‚ÇÅ)

# Tandem DMA equations
T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) = Œ¥.Œ©(Œõ, Œ¥.Z, zÀ¢ / k) .* Œ¥.Tc(k, Œ¥.Dp) .* Œ¥.Tl(Œõ, Œ¥.Dp)
DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ, Œ¥) =
    sum(map(k -> (ztod(Œõ, 1, zÀ¢) / ztod(Œõ, k, zÀ¢)) ‚ãÖ (gf ‚ãÖ (T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) * ùïü)), 1:3))
DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥) = Œ¥.ùêé * ùïü
model(zÀ¢, gf) = DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü·∂ú‚Åø, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ‚ÇÅ, Œ¥‚ÇÅ) |> ùïü -> DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥‚ÇÇ)

P = [0.5,0.15, 0.10, 0.25]   # Probability of growth factor (4 populations)
gf = [1.0, 1.2, 1.6, 2.1]    # Values of growth factor
zÀ¢ = dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 100e-9)        # Mobility of 100 nm particle
ùïû = sum(map(i->(P[i]*model(zÀ¢, gf[i])), 1:length(P)))  # The growth factor distribution

See the Manuscript and notebook S8 in the Notebooks section for partial charge distribution, and for examples involving the use of a second neutralizer in line.

Grid Mismatch

In the above examples, the grids for DMA‚ÇÅ and DMA‚ÇÇ were identical. This is usually not the case. The DMAs are operated in different size ranges, flow regimes and may be of different physical design. To address this, the output of DMA‚ÇÅ can be intpolated onto the grid of DMA‚ÇÇ using the interpolateSizeDistributionOntoŒ¥ function. 

model(zÀ¢, gf) =
    (DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü·∂ú‚Åø, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ‚ÇÅ, Œ¥‚ÇÅ), Œ¥‚ÇÇ) |> interpolateSizeDistributionOntoŒ¥ |> ùïü -> DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥‚ÇÇ)

The example below demonstrates how this works for two DMAs of different designs.

t, p = 295.15, 1e5
qsa, qsh = 1.66e-5, 8.33e-5

# Standard TSI DMA
r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l = 9.37e-3, 1.961e-2, 0.44369
Œõ‚ÇÅ = DMAconfig(t, p, qsa, qsh, r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l, 0.0, :-, 3, :cylindrical)
Œ¥‚ÇÅ = setupDMA(Œõ‚ÇÅ, dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 500e-9), dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 30e-9), 120)

# High-Flow DMA
r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l = 0.05, 0.058, 0.6
Œõ‚ÇÇ = DMAconfig(t, p, qsa, qsh, r‚ÇÅ, r‚ÇÇ, l, 0.0, :-, 3, :cylindrical)
Œ¥‚ÇÇ = setupDMA(Œõ‚ÇÇ, dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÇ, 250e-9), dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÇ, 50e-9), 60)

# Upstream Size Distribution
Ax = [[1300.0, 60.0, 1.4], [2000.0, 200.0, 1.6]]
ùïü·∂ú‚Åø = DMALognormalDistribution(Ax, Œ¥‚ÇÅ)

# Tandem DMA equations
T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) = Œ¥.Œ©(Œõ, Œ¥.Z, zÀ¢ / k) .* Œ¥.Tc(k, Œ¥.Dp) .* Œ¥.Tl(Œõ, Œ¥.Dp)
DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ, Œ¥) =
    sum(map(k -> (ztod(Œõ, 1, zÀ¢) / ztod(Œõ, k, zÀ¢)) ‚ãÖ (gf ‚ãÖ (T(zÀ¢, k, Œõ, Œ¥) * ùïü)), 1:3))
DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥) = Œ¥.ùêé * ùïü

model(zÀ¢, gf) =
    (DMA‚ÇÅ(ùïü·∂ú‚Åø, zÀ¢, gf, Œõ‚ÇÅ, Œ¥‚ÇÅ), Œ¥‚ÇÇ) |> interpolateSizeDistributionOntoŒ¥ |> ùïü -> DMA‚ÇÇ(ùïü, Œ¥‚ÇÇ)

zÀ¢ = dtoz(Œõ‚ÇÅ, 100e-9);   # Mobility of 100 nm particle
gf = 1.55                # Growth factor

# Pass size distribution to DMA‚ÇÅ and then output distributiom to DMA‚ÇÇ
ùïû = model(zÀ¢, gf)
P = [0.5, 0.15, 0.10, 0.25]   # Probability of growth factor (4 populations)
gf = [1.0, 1.2, 1.6, 2.1]    # Values of growth factor
ùïû = sum(map(i -> (P[i] * model(zÀ¢, gf[i])), 1:length(P)))  # The growth factor distribution
